 Durrell.\n5:15 Argentine Trio.\nUoUender\netty.\n5:30\n5:45 Sons of Pioneers\u2014Gordon's\nJewelry Co.\n6:00 Texaco Firechlef News Flashes.\n6:15 Rialto Theatre Program.\n6:30 Montana Power Company.\n6:45 Pinsel's Program.\n7:00 Butte's Merry Xmas Program.\n7:30 American Family Robinson.\n7:45 Khorey and Sons.\n8:00 Emil Maran's Fashion Parade.\n8:15 Quartette Selections.\n8:30 Celia Gamba, Violinist.\n9:00 Texaco Firechief News Flashes.\n9:15 LaSalle Hotel Orchestra.\n9:30 Jimmie Dorsey Orchestra.\n10:00 Ambassador Hotel Orchestra.\n10:30 St. Francis Hotel Orchestra.\n11:00 Mea kin's Musical News.\n11:10 Dance Time TUI Midnight.\nWEDNESDAY, DECEMBER 1\nOrchestra.\n8:00 Pay'n Save Musical Clock.\n8:15 Vaughn DeLeath.\n8:30 Bennett and Wolverton.\n8:45 Monarch Lumber Co.\n9:00 Financial Service.\n9:15 Savemore Market Flashes.\n9:30 Weather Bulletins from Helena.\n9:31 Montana Flour Mills\u2014Martha West.\n9:45 Larry Larson, Organist.\n10:00 Time for Thought.\n10:15 Edward Gamage.\n10:30 National F\n11:30 Sue Blake.\n11:45 Montana Hardware Co.\n12:00 Texaco Firechief News Flashes.\n12:15 Butte's Merry Christmas Program.\n12:45 Eddy's Bakery Presents Knights of\nthe Road.\n1:00 Oechsli's Organ Treasures.\n1:15 Oxydol's Own Ma Perkins.\n1:30 Crisco's Vic and Sade.\n1:45 Lydia Pinkham.\n2:00 Livestock\n2:15 Club Matinee.\n2:30 Good Afternoon Neighbors.\n3:15 Don Winslow of the Navy.\n3:30 Anaconda's Merry Xmas Program.\n3:45 Glass Hat Room Orchestra.\n4:00 America's School.\n4:15 Stevens Hotel Orchestra.\n4:30 Maytag Shop.\n4:45 Escorts and Betty.\n5:00 Joseph Hornik Orchestra.\n5:30 La Conga Orchestra.\n5:45 Sons of Pioneers\u2014Gordon's\nJewelry Co.\n6:00 Texaco Firechief News Flashes.\n6:15 Let's Go to the Theatre.\nKhorey and Sons.\nPinsel's Program.\n7:00 Butte's Merry Xmas Program.\n7:30 NBC Minstrels.\n8:00 Your Lucky Strike Hit Parade.\n8:45 Cystex Program.\n9:00 Texaco Firechief News Flashes.\n9:15 Rainbow Trio.\n9:30 Chez Parce Orchestra.\n10:00 Eddie Rogers Orchestra.\n10:30 Savoy Ballroom Orchestra.\n11:10 Dance Time Until Midnight.\nHome Hour,\nShow.\ni.i\n6:45\nQUOTED FROM THE VOICE OF\nEXPERIENCE\n\"Several have written\naccusing me\nof making up my own problems. I*\nbeen accused e\nair, because of the unusual character of\nmany problems I have broadcast, of\nhaving a fertile imagination in making\nmy broadcasts. Fortunately,\nfile the original letter for every problem\nI have broadcast In the last six years.\"\n\"The six cardinal traits in anyone's per\nsonaUty are: emotionaJ stablUty, self\nsufficiency, extroversion, dominance, self\nconfidence, and sociability. And these are\nnot pet characteristics of mine; they are\nthe six chosen by outstanding phycholo\ngists of today. An extrovert is one who\nlives largely in the lives of others, where\nas an introvert is inclined, at the least\nprovocation, to draw within his (or her)\nshell.\"\nListen to the Voice of Experience Mon\nday through Friday over KGIR at 1:45\nsince I've been\nthe\nhave\nP\nBrewers Pledged to Public Interest\n'i\n\nk?\n\nTbc\nM\ncjoncui\n\u25a0'4\u00c2 \u00eerJ\nL\nV*\n\n\nHere are two officers o( the Uulted Brewers Industrial Foundation\nhown signing the brewers' Code of Practice at the Foundation's conven\ntion in Pittsburgh. With pen poised Is S. E. Abrams, second vice chairman\nof the Foundation and vice president and general manager of the Schlitz\nBrewing Company, Milwaukee. The other brewer is H, J. Charles, newly\nelected chairman of the Foundation and secretary of the Theo, Hamm\nBrewing Co., St. Paul, Minn.\nFLATHEAD CENTRAL\nTRADES AND LABOR\nCOUNCIL ORGANIZED\n(Continued from Page 1)\nin the Kalispell hall and all meet\nings, except executive sessions are\nopen to any union worker with a\ncard showing him to be in good\nstanding with his local organization.\nThose active in bringing about the\nnew organization have already re\nceived the endorsement and assur\nance of cooperation of both state and\nnational officers of the American\nFederation of Labor with which all\nmembers of the local body are affili\nated.\nRoster of Delegates of the Flathead\nCentral Trades and Labor Coun\ncil, Kalispell, Montana\nInternational Brotherhood of Elec\ntrical Workers, No. 768: Eldo Collier,\nvice president; Ingvald Anderson,\nbusiness agent; Bernard Horstman,\ndelegate.\nChauffeurs, Teamsters and Help\ners, No. 593: Chas. G, Graves, busi\nness agent; A. L. Chapman, presi\ndent; S. W. Prather, delegate.\nInternational Hod Carriers, Build\ning and Common Laborers Union of\nAmerica, No. 1192: Joe Dzivi, presi\ndent and business agent; Francis S.\nJune, delegate; Oscar Torgerson,\ndelegate and recording secretary.\nOperative Plasterers and Cement\nFinishers International Association,\nNo. 436; A. J. Hale, delegate; Harold\nL. Hiebert, secretary; Clarence R.\nRiddle, delegate.\nInternational Asociation of Ma\nchinists, No. 1232: Norman E. Bjorne\nby, Ivan Jennings, and C, S. Brown,\ndelegates.\nCarpenters and Jointers Interna\ntional, No. 911: A. E. Mercer, dele\ngate; E. W. Kind, business agent;\nEric Naethe, financial secretary.\nBrotherhood of Painters, Decora\ntors and Paperhangers of America,\nNo. 975: Perry Melton, secretary; F.\nW. Pierce, trustee; Fred Meacham,\ntreasurer.\nKalispell Typographical Union, No.\n723: G. B. Baker, president; E. D,\nBrooner, vice president; Albert Law\nlor, secretary-treasurer.\nCapital Responsible\nFor Work Curtailment\n(Continued from Page 1)\nfifth of the entire working force\u2014is\nthe first result.\n\"The Anaconda Copper Mining\nCompany, in the first six months of\nthis year, made a net profit of $20,\n000,000 in round figures. This was\na 229 per cent increase over the net\nprofit in the same period of last year.\n\"The A. C. M., with other big cop\nper companies, has agreed to cut\nproduction 20 to 25 per cent\u2014and to\nlay off enough men to effect this\nreduction. Not the A. C. M. and its\nmonopoly capital associates are to\nbear the burden of this reduction\u2014\nbut miners and smelterworkers.\n\"That there are political motives\nbehind the sudden increase in un\nemployment throughout the country\nis proven by the statement of a local\nA. C. M. official who informed a\ncommittee of the Butte Miners Un\nion that the layoffs are due in part\nto the uncertainty about what Roose\nvelt and the special session of Con\ngress are going to do.\n\"In the last session of Congress the\nhenchmen of reaction knifed vital\nlabor and farm legislation. These\nsame reactionaries have been en\ncouraged by their success in the last\nsession, especially by their defeat of\nthe President's Supreme Court re\nform plan. Big Business is prepar\ning to go further. They are now\nconspiring to bring on economically\nunwarranted depression in order to\ndefeat necessary labor and farm leg\nislation. Capitalism is plotting a sit\ndown strike against American re\ncovery.\n\"Big capital is deliberately plotting\nManufacture ol Beer\nUnder Federal Laws\nRaises Moral Level\nWhen we reflect back on the tur\nmoil, law violations, and the rackets\nwhich accompanied the illegal sale\nof beer during the hectic days of\nprohibition, the attitude and high\nethical standards of the United\nBrewers Industrial Foundation\nstrikes us like a refreshing breeze.\nThe Brewers code of practice pledges\nthem to honesty, sobriety and law\nacknowledgement. We never want\nthe conditions of Capone and other\nhomebrew barons to return. Indus\ntry within the law conducted by re\nsponsible persons, is something we\nhave learned to respect through bit\nter experience. The code of the\nUnited Brewers is as follows;\nTHE BREWERS'\nCODE OF PRACTICE\nThe Brewing Industry of the\nUnited States, custodian of an art\nand science practiced since the be\nginnings of recorded history, sup\nplies a mild beverage to the major\npart of our population. Beer is the\nbulwark of moderation and sobriety.\nThe industry recognizes its direct re\nsponsibility to itself and to the na\ntion to conduct its operations in ac\ncord with the desires and conscience\nof the American public. Members\nof the United Brewers Industrial\nFoundation, in convention assembled,\nrepresenting nearly half the produc\ntion of beer and ale in the United\nStates, mutually and individually\npledge themselves to the following\nCode of Practice;\nWe pledge ourselves, as citizens\nand as business men, to conduct our\nbusine:\nin conformity with estab\nlished laws in cooperation with the\nauthorities.\nWe pledge ourselves as\nbrewers to maintain exacting high\nstandards in the brewing and pack\naging of beer and ale.\nWe pledge ourselves, with all\nthoughtful citizens, to the promotion\nof practical moderation and sobriety.\nWe pledge our support to the duly\nconstituted authorities for the elimi\nnation of anti-social conditions wher\never they may surround the sale of\nbeer to the consumer.\nWe pledge ourselves morally to\nsupport and encourage the great\nbody of retailers who sell beer as\nlaw-abiding citizens and who oper\nate legal, respectable premises.\nWe pledge ourselves to cooperate\nwith the duly constituted authorities\nto prevent beer sales to minors, or to\npersons who have drunk to excess.\nWe pledge ourselves to truth in\nthe advertising of beer.\nWe pledge ourselves faithfully to\nobserve the provisions of this Code\nof Practice, convinced that beer is\nthe nation's bulwark of moderation\nand sobriety.\nintific\nplus Bedaux stretchout.\nto curtail production, in order to\nprovoke a \"panic\" to frighten the\nmiddle classes. These Tories are\ncold-bloodedly gambling with the\nprospects of American recovery and\nare endangering the welfare of the\nAmerican people.\n\"Their immediate aim is to put a\nstop to all necessary social, labor\nand farm legislation. They want to\ndrastically cut the appropriations for\nwork relief for the unemployed.\nThey want to repeal the taxes on\ntheir undistributed profits. They\nwant the government to increase\nloans to big industry through the\nReconstruction Finance Corporation.\nBig Business itself is on the dole\nand is clamoring for a bigger budget.\n\"If they succeed in carrying out\ntheir nefarious plans they will\nfurther cut the purchasing power\nof the workers, farmers and middle\nclass people of the country\u2014the real\npeople of America.\"\nDuke's mixture: Nazi Labor Front\nP. S. Not popular on this side of\nthe ocean.\nMontana Gels Increase\nOf 1,090 in WPS Quota\n(Continued from Page 1)\ntils connected with\nevident that Mon\nno\ntelegram, it\na's Senior Senator went to see\nAdministration\nthe Works Progi\nat Washington and helped obtain ad\nditional funds. It will be noted that\nthe telegram states that one thou\nsand additional men will be taken\nby the government. These\nthousand men, it is estimated will\nneed to be re-employed by the WPA\nin order to take care of the situation\nincurred in the layoffs by the Ana\nconda Company.\nSenator Wheeler's telegram is as\nfollows;\nare\n\"Glad to say that WPA has author\nized additional funds for Montana to\nemploy about a thousand additional\nmen to alleviate situation caused by\nACM layoffs. B. K. Wheeler.\"\nCongressman Jerry J. O'Connell is\nfied with the situation here\nindicated by his telegram which\nnot S\nfollows:\n\"Am not satisfied with one thou\nsand man quota increase thus far\nsecured on Butte WPA stiuation. Am\ndemanding further incre\nsisting that such increases at least\nbe consistent with constant Anaconda\nCompany layoffs. I am continuing\nmy efforts with WPA officials and\nwill do everything possible to secure\nadditional quota increase. As long\nas Anaconda Company refuses to do\nits share toward maintaining recov\nery I feel it incumbent on the ad\nministration to do everything pos\nsible for all of these men thrown out\nof work in Butte. Jerry J. O'Con\nnell.\"\n;s and in\nIS THIS BUSINESS\nRECESSION!\nEXTENSION OF REMARKS\nOf\nHON. JERRY J. O'CONNELL\nof Montana, in the House of Repre\nsentatives, Wednesday, Novem\nber 17, 1937.\nMr. O'Connell of Montana, Mr.\nSpeaker, under leave to extend\nmy remarks, I wish to include here\nin an Associated Press dispatch from\nNew York of November 12, showing\nthat the income of the Anaconda\npper Mining Co, for the 9 months\nending September 30, 1937, amount\ned to $36,965,194, equal to $3.11\nDuring this same period in\n1936, their income amounted to $9,\n940,132 or $1.15 a share. In other\nwords, for the first 9 months of 1937\ntheir income was $27,025,062 or $1.96\na share more than the same period\nin 1936. Can this be the business\nrecession which we hear so much\ntalk about today? Is this the un\nwholesome situation which capital\ncomplains so much about?\nNotwithstanding this tremendous\nincome, the Anaconda Copper Min\ning Co. is closing its mines in Butte,\nMont., and is throwing thousands of\nmen out of work. It is evident that\nthe Anaconda Copper Mining Co.,\nalong with all the other wealthy\ncorporations in the United States, are\npurposely causing this so-called\nbusiness recession in an effort to\nsabotage the New Deal and frighten\nthis Congress into granting all of\nthese great corporations tax conces\nsions to which they are not entitled.\nThere is no need for the mines in\nButte being closed. There is no need\nfor the thousands of miners in Butte\nto be thrown out of work.\nThe Associated Press dispatch,\nwhich I quote below, shows that this\nwealthy corporation is making ample\nmoney. In order to mold public\nopinion in the State of Montana, the\nAnaconda Copper Mining Co. owns\npractically all of the daily news\npapers within the State of Montana.\nTheir Montana Standard, Butte Daily\nPost, Daily Missoulian, Missoula\nSentinel, Helena Independent, Hel\nena Record Herald, Billings Gazette,\nand Livingston Enterprise are oper\nated at a tremendous loss. The Ana\nconda Copper Mining Co. has suffi\ncient money to continue running\nthose newspapers even though they\nare a steadily losing proposition, but\nthey have no money to put starving\nminers in Butte, Mont., to work.\nI am at a loss to understand why\nthis Congress should give any\nthought whatsoever to the question\nof granting tax concessions to any\nof these corporations, in view of the\nconcerted effort which they are all\nmaking to thwart recovery. Let this\nCongress exert itself to enact legisla\ntion for the benefit of those who\nhave not. Those who have seem to\ndo a pretty good job of looking after\nthemselves.\nA. C. M. EARNS $3.11 A SHARE ON\n9 MONTHS OF BUSINESS,\nIT REPORTS\nNew York, November 12.\u2014Ana\nconda Copper Mining Co and sub\nsidiary companies said today con\nsolidated income for the 9 months\nended September 30 amounted to\n$36,965,194, equal to $3.11 a share on\n8,674,338 shares of capital stock.\nEquity in undistributed earnings\nof subsidiaries not consolidated and\nnot included in the consolidated in\ncome account totaled $1,569,085, or\n18 cents a share.\nNet income in the comparable 1936\nperiod stood at $9,940,132, or $1.15 a\nshare.\na\nbar\nPATRONIZE OUR ADVERTISERS I\nLEGAL NOTICES\nNOTICE OF\niEIZURE.\nIn the District\nus. District ol\nUNITED\n.S OF\nAMERICA. L\nant. v. F\npart\nami Turn;\nand Cel\nPacked for\nUtah.\n\nMooie, Pa\nDime Bottlers\nNOTICE IS\nlibel lor cou\nby the libelant,\nilea\nCu\u201e uic., Libuie*\n1Y G1VLN tout a\nby orae\nect\ntne\ned on land,\nButie, Silver Bow county. Montana,\nwithin tne jurisdiction of this Court,\nfollowing described property, to-wit:\nless, each containing\narticle labeled in\nCelto Brand Tomato\nCelery Juice, Net Weight 12 Oz.,\npacked for Blake and Blackington. Ogden,\nickeu under Heatn anu Moore.\nPatent Pending.' That libelant prays in\nsaid libel tor condemnation that said prop\nerty be condemned and forfeited to the\nUnited States oi America upon the follow\ning grounds: I. That Woods Cross Can\nning Co. shipped from Clearfield, Utah, in\nrsiate commerce and transported\nland by way of the Union Pacific Rail\nroad and Butte, Anaconda Pacific Rail\nway Company, to Butte, in the County of\nSilver Bow, in the State and District of\nMontana, and within the jurisdiction of\nthis Court, certain articles which may be\nused as food, to-wit: said tour cases, more\nor less, each containing forty-eight cans\ne labeled in part on said\nCelery Juice,\nWeight 12 Oz., Packed for Blake\nUtah, Packed unuei\nPatern Penning\"; that\nerem men\n-eight ca\npai\nmi\nIt'ii\nat ail\nve uteu, and\nfood foi\nbale\nntana; and\nntained\nas articles c\nand District\n\u25a0tides\nill tile Eli\nfoo\neach con\nadulterated\nviolation oi section 7, Paragraph Sixth\n8, Title 21, U. S, C.) of the Food\nand Drugs Act, in the case of food, in that\nsaid article consists wholly or in part of\ndecomposed vegetable substance; and that\nsaid articles of food contained In said four\ncases, more or less, each containing forty\neight cans, as aforesaid, are misbranded,\nin violation of Section 8, Paragraph Fifth,\nSection 10, Title 21, U. S. C.) of the Food\nand Drugs Act in the case of food in that\nit is canned food and falls below the\nstandard of quality and condition promul\ngated by the Secretary of Agriculture for\nsuch canned food in that said articles of\nfood show chemical decomposition and its\npackage or lable does not bear a plain\nand conspicuous statement prescribed by\nthe Secretary of Agriculture indicating\nthat such canned food falls below such\nstandard; contrary ot the form, force and\neffect of the statute in such\nana provided, and against the peace and\ndignity of the United States of America.\nNOTICE IS FURTHER GIVEN that, by\norder of Court, all libelees herein named,\nand all persons ha\nany interest in said property,\nbeiore specifically described a\nhaving anything to say why the same\nshould not be condemned and forfeited,\nappear and file their respective answers,\nclaims and defenses to such libel for con\ndemnation, setting forth their interest in\nor claim to the said property\nthe Clerk of the United St\nCourt, at B